irtual supply offers ... 13 \nFigure 2-14 Cleared virtual transactions as a percent of load ... 14 \nFigure 2-15 Virtual demand bids by participant type ... 15 \nFigure 2-16 Virtual supply offers by participant type ... 15 \nFigure 2-17 Virtual transactions by location type, volume ... 16 \nFigure 2-18 Virtual transactions by location type, profit/loss before fees ... 16 \nFigure 2-19 Virtual transactions, profit/loss (before and after fees) ... 17 \nFigure 2-20 Virtual transactions, profit/loss per MW (before and after fees) ... 18 \nFigure 3-1 Peak hour capacity overage, real-time average ... 20 \nFigure 3-2 Day-ahead physical resources offered by status ... 21 \nFigure 3-3 Percentage of megawatts dispatched by commitment status ... 22 \nFigure 3-4 On-line capacity as a percent of demand ... 23 \nFigure 3-5 Scarcity intervals and marginal energy cost, real-time ... 24 \nFigure 3-6 Generation outages and derates, by fuel type ... 25 \nFigure 3-7 Curtailments for wind resources ... 26 \nFigure 4-1 Electricity and gas prices ... 28 \nFigure 4-2 Implied heat rate ... 29 \nFigure 4-3 Price divergence, day-ahead and real-time ... 30 \nFigure 4-4 Price map, summer (off-peak) ... 31 \nFigure 4-5 Price map, summer (on-peak) ... 31 \nFigure 4-6 Price by load-serving entity, summer ... 32 \nFigure 4-7 Price by load-serving entity, rolling 12 month ... 32 \nFigure 4-8 Trading hub prices ... 33 \nFigure 4-9 North hub prices, on-peak and off-peak ... 34 \nFigure 4-10 South hub prices, on-peak and off-peak ... 34 \nFigure 4-11 Negative price intervals, day-ahead ... 35 \nFigure 4-12 Negative price intervals, real-time ... 36 \nFigure 4-13 Regulation-up prices ... 37 \nFigure 4-14 Regulation-down prices ... 37 \n\nSouthwest Power Pool, Inc. Figures Market Monitoring Unit\n\nState of the Market Summer 2024 iv\n\nFigure 4-15 Spinning reserve prices ... 39 \nFigure 4-16 Supplemental reserve prices ... 39 \nFigure 4-17 Ramp product prices ... 40 \nFigure 4-18 Uncertainty product shortage intervals ... 41 \nFigure 4-19 Mitigation frequency, day-ahead market ... 42 \nFigure 4-20 Mitigation frequency, real-time market ... 43 \nFigure 4-21 Mitigation frequency, start-up offers ... 43 \nFigure 4-22 Make-whole payments, day-ahead ... 44 \nFigure 4-23 Make-whole payments, reliability unit commitment ... 45 \nFigure 4-24 Revenue neutrality uplift ... 45 \nFigure 5-1 Congestion by shadow price, summer ... 48 \nFigure 5-2 Congestion by shadow price, rolling 12 month ... 49 \nFigure 5-3 Congestion by interval, day-ahead ... 50 \nFigure 5-4 Congestion by interval, real-time ... 51 \nFigure 5-5 Total congestion payments, summer ... 51 \nFigure 5-6 Day-ahead, net congestion revenue by market participant, summer ... 52 \nFigure 5-7 Day-ahead and real-time, net congestion revenue by market participant, summer \n ... 53 \nFigure 5-8 Transmission congestion right funding, month and quarter ... 54 \nFigure 5-9 Transmission congestion right funding, summer ... 54 \nFigure 5-10 Auction revenue right funding, month and quarter ... 55 \nFigure 6-1 Outages by type ... 56 \nFigure 6-2 Load versus forecast ... 57 \nFigure 6-3 Wind versus forecast ... 57 \nFigure 6-4 Net imports and exports ... 58 \nFigure 6-5 Day-ahead and real-time prices ... 59 \n\nSouthwest Power Pool, Inc. Market highlights Market Monitoring Unit\n\n### 1 MARKET HIGHLIGHTS\n\nThis report covers market performance and highlights during the 2024 summer quarter (June through August). Annual figures shown on the charts in this report represent only this three month period for each year, unless labelled otherwise. Highlights of this summer period are as follows:\n\n• After peaking around $8/MMBtu in summer 2022, the average gas price at the Panhandle Eastern hub has been in the $2/MMBtu range since February 2023, with the exception of January 2024, which was higher as a result of a winter weather event. Since January 2024, the average gas price has ranged from $1.26/MMBtu to $1.70/MMBtu. Overall, the average gas price was down by 23 percent in summer 2024 in comparison with 2023, with an average price of $1.65/MMBtu in summer 2024. \n• Day-ahead prices decreased from $35/MWh in summer 2023 to $29/MWh in 2024, a decrease of 17 percent. Real-time prices also decreased 17 percent, from an average of $32/MWh in summer 2023 to $27/MWh in 2024. This decrease in prices is driven predominantly by the lower gas prices experienced during this period. \n• Total day-ahead make-whole payments were up from $19.1 million in summer 2023 to $22.4 million in 2024. Outside of January 2024, day-ahead make-whole payments were in the $5 million to $10 million dollar range for the last 15 months. \n• Total reliability unit commitment make-whole payments were down from $58.9 million in summer 2023 to $41.3 million in 2024. Gas resources, particularly simple-cycle resources, accounted for most of the decrease. Much of the decrease compared to summer 2023 can be attributed to a decrease in natural gas prices. \n• Total revenue neutrality uplift for summer 2024 was $42 million, up from $21 million in 2023. The change can be mostly attributed to higher levels of real-time congestion in summer 2024. \n\n• Average hourly load for the 2024 summer season was three percent above 2023, while the peak hourly load was down three percent compared to 2023.\n\n• Wind generation was the primary technology type in terms of generation during the summer 2024 quarter, accounting for 30 percent of total generation, an increase from 24 percent in 2023. Coal generation decreased from 34 percent of total generation in summer 2023 to 28 percent in 2024. 2024 is the first summer season when wind generation surpassed coal in terms of percentage of total generation, mostly buoyed by \n\nSouthwest Power Pool, Inc. Market highlights Market Monitoring Unit\n\nState of the Market Summer 2024 2 much higher wind generation during June. Both gas, simple-cycle and gas, combined cycle generation climbed slightly from summer 